</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Treatment of thoracic aortic dissection remains highly challenging and is rapidly evolving. Common classifications of thoracic aortic dissection include the Stanford classification (types A and B) and the DeBakey classification (types I to III), as well as a new supplementary classification geared toward endovascular decision making. By using various imaging techniques, the extent of the dissection, the location of the primary intimal tear, the shape of the aortic arch, and the zonal involvement of the aortic arch—factors that affect the treatment strategy—can easily be identified. Thoracic endovascular aortic repair (TEVAR) is generally performed in two groups of patients: <i>(a)</i> those with a surgically repaired type A dissection, and <i>(b)</i> those with a complicated type B dissection. Several imaging findings can help predict the course of remodeling of the dissected aorta after a repaired type A dissection and TEVAR. A spectrum of imaging findings exist with regard to favorable (positive) or failing (negative) remodeling. A schematic model with imaging support allows the classification of important causes of failing remodeling into proximal and distal groups, on the basis of the origin of the refilling of the false lumen and the underlying pathophysiology of pressurization. Refilling of the false lumen of the aorta after repair of a type A dissection is usually secondary to a persistent intimal tear at the aortic arch, a leak of the distal graft anastomosis, or refilling from the false lumen of a dissected aortic arch vessel. After TEVAR, false lumen refilling is most commonly due to an incomplete seal of the proximal landing related to the aortic tortuosity, an arch branch stump, a supra-arch chimney stent, or the TEVAR technique.</div><div role="paragraph"><i>Online supplemental material is available for this article.</i></div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2018</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018180025">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2018180025">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig1.jpeg" height="1835" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Flowchart shows treatment of thoracic aortic dissection that is based on the Stanford classification of aortic dissection. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>DA</i> = descending aorta, <i>ET</i> = elephant trunk, <i>F/U</i> = follow-up.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig2.jpeg" height="1222" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Anatomic drawings of surgical procedures for type A aortic dissection. Black arrows = favorable flow in the true lumen, blue arrows = favorable flow, white arrows = persistent flow into the false lumen. <i>1</i>, Primary supracoronary ascending aorta replacement with peninsula-style transverse arch (hemiarch) replacement. <i>2, 3,</i> Primary ascending aorta repair with total arch (elephant trunk) replacement. Complete repair can be performed as shown: <i>2,</i> by using secondary immediate antegrade TEVAR (hybrid operation), or, <i>3,</i> by using delayed retrograde TEVAR. <i>4,</i> Frozen elephant trunk including a multibranch total arch replacement and antegrade TEVAR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig3a.jpeg" height="1186" width="1560" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Primary repair of type A aortic dissection in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered anterior and posterior CT images show primary supracoronary ascending aorta <i>(AA)</i> replacement. Residual dissection is evident in the rest of the aorta, with extension into the arch vessels. Follow-up CT was performed to assess for signs of aortic dilatation and malperfusion. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic images after a Bentall procedure show some of the required aortic measurements. All aortic diameters should be determined on a true axial view of the aorta (inset on <b>c</b>), as shown for the maximum aortic diameter (double-headed black arrow on <b>c</b>). A large primary intimal tear (&gt;10 mm) (red double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) in the proximal descending aorta, a false lumen diameter (pink double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) of more than 22 mm, and luminal expansion of 1 cm or more within 1 year are some of the warning indicators to consider performing TEVAR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig3b.jpeg" height="1186" width="1108" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Primary repair of type A aortic dissection in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered anterior and posterior CT images show primary supracoronary ascending aorta <i>(AA)</i> replacement. Residual dissection is evident in the rest of the aorta, with extension into the arch vessels. Follow-up CT was performed to assess for signs of aortic dilatation and malperfusion. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic images after a Bentall procedure show some of the required aortic measurements. All aortic diameters should be determined on a true axial view of the aorta (inset on <b>c</b>), as shown for the maximum aortic diameter (double-headed black arrow on <b>c</b>). A large primary intimal tear (&gt;10 mm) (red double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) in the proximal descending aorta, a false lumen diameter (pink double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) of more than 22 mm, and luminal expansion of 1 cm or more within 1 year are some of the warning indicators to consider performing TEVAR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig3c.jpeg" height="1186" width="1031" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Primary repair of type A aortic dissection in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered anterior and posterior CT images show primary supracoronary ascending aorta <i>(AA)</i> replacement. Residual dissection is evident in the rest of the aorta, with extension into the arch vessels. Follow-up CT was performed to assess for signs of aortic dilatation and malperfusion. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and sagittal <b>(c)</b> CT angiographic images after a Bentall procedure show some of the required aortic measurements. All aortic diameters should be determined on a true axial view of the aorta (inset on <b>c</b>), as shown for the maximum aortic diameter (double-headed black arrow on <b>c</b>). A large primary intimal tear (&gt;10 mm) (red double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) in the proximal descending aorta, a false lumen diameter (pink double-headed arrow on <b>c</b>) of more than 22 mm, and luminal expansion of 1 cm or more within 1 year are some of the warning indicators to consider performing TEVAR.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig4.jpeg" height="2269" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Classification of the proximal landing zones. Left anterior oblique CT image shows the locations of the proximal landing zones on the aortic arch. Successful TEVAR requires a healthy proximal landing zone with an adequate diameter (25–40 mm) and length (15–20 mm). Most TEVAR procedures for aortic dissection involve proximal landing zone 2 of the aortic arch, followed by zone 3 as the second most common. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LSCA</i> = left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig5.jpeg" height="1372" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Influence of the shape of the aortic arch (angulation and tortuosity) on the proximal landing zones. Left anterior oblique CT images show the classification of variation in the angulation and tortuosity of the aortic arch; the classification is based on the vertical distance (double-headed arrows) from the origin of the innominate artery (lower line) to the top of the arch (upper line): type I, distance less than one diameter of the left common carotid artery; type II, distance between one and two diameters of the left common carotid artery; and type III, distance more than two diameters of the left common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig6a.jpeg" height="1293" width="1267" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Incomplete coverage of the proximal landing zone in a 69-year-old man with a Stanford type B aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the primary intimal tear (yellow arrow) in proximal landing zone 4. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows that the deployed stent has not covered the tear (yellow arrow). <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT image shows distal positioning of the stent relative to the orifice of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i>. Incomplete exclusion of the primary tear owing to an insufficient proximal seal or endograft migration may lead to continued false lumen filling and a poor treatment outcome. In this case, the surgeon has to go back and place another stent more proximally after a short follow-up time. <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig6b.jpeg" height="1293" width="1225" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Incomplete coverage of the proximal landing zone in a 69-year-old man with a Stanford type B aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the primary intimal tear (yellow arrow) in proximal landing zone 4. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows that the deployed stent has not covered the tear (yellow arrow). <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT image shows distal positioning of the stent relative to the orifice of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i>. Incomplete exclusion of the primary tear owing to an insufficient proximal seal or endograft migration may lead to continued false lumen filling and a poor treatment outcome. In this case, the surgeon has to go back and place another stent more proximally after a short follow-up time. <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig6c.jpeg" height="1293" width="1205" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Incomplete coverage of the proximal landing zone in a 69-year-old man with a Stanford type B aortic dissection. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows the primary intimal tear (yellow arrow) in proximal landing zone 4. <b>(b)</b> Axial CT angiographic image shows that the deployed stent has not covered the tear (yellow arrow). <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone. <b>(c)</b> Posterior volume-rendered CT image shows distal positioning of the stent relative to the orifice of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i>. Incomplete exclusion of the primary tear owing to an insufficient proximal seal or endograft migration may lead to continued false lumen filling and a poor treatment outcome. In this case, the surgeon has to go back and place another stent more proximally after a short follow-up time. <i>PLZ</i> = proximal landing zone.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig7a.jpeg" height="1755" width="1389" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Intentional left subclavian artery coverage without revascularization in a 67-year-old man. Sagittal maximum intensity projection image <b>(a)</b> and lateral volume-rendered CT image <b>(b)</b> show complete coverage of the orifice of the left subclavian artery (<i>LSCA</i> on <b>b</b>) after plugging (with use of an Amplatzer [Abbott, St Paul, Minn] occluder) the proximal left subclavian artery (red arrow) via the left brachial artery, causing left subclavian steal by the left vertebral artery. Other possible complications of this approach include spinal cord ischemia, left upper limb ischemia, and a stroke in the vertebral artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig7b.jpeg" height="1755" width="1562" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Intentional left subclavian artery coverage without revascularization in a 67-year-old man. Sagittal maximum intensity projection image <b>(a)</b> and lateral volume-rendered CT image <b>(b)</b> show complete coverage of the orifice of the left subclavian artery (<i>LSCA</i> on <b>b</b>) after plugging (with use of an Amplatzer [Abbott, St Paul, Minn] occluder) the proximal left subclavian artery (red arrow) via the left brachial artery, causing left subclavian steal by the left vertebral artery. Other possible complications of this approach include spinal cord ischemia, left upper limb ischemia, and a stroke in the vertebral artery territory.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig8a.jpeg" height="1625" width="1704" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. In situ laser fenestration of the stent-graft to place a left subclavian artery stent (yellow arrow) in a 62-year-old man. Frontal catheter angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and frontal volume-rendered CT image <b>(b)</b> show the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> and stent after fenestration of the stent-graft. Inset on <b>b</b>: Axial CT image shows the left subclavian artery stent passing the wall of the stent-graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig8b.jpeg" height="1625" width="1254" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. In situ laser fenestration of the stent-graft to place a left subclavian artery stent (yellow arrow) in a 62-year-old man. Frontal catheter angiographic image <b>(a)</b> and frontal volume-rendered CT image <b>(b)</b> show the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> and stent after fenestration of the stent-graft. Inset on <b>b</b>: Axial CT image shows the left subclavian artery stent passing the wall of the stent-graft.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig9a.jpeg" height="1286" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Chimney stent technique with parastent endoleak in a 64-year-old man. Catheter angiographic <b>(a)</b>, volume-rendered CT <b>(b)</b>, coronal CT <b>(c)</b>, and axial CT <b>(d)</b> images show deployment of a left common carotid artery stent (yellow arrow) parallel to the thoracic stent-graft. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. Axial CT image <b>(d)</b> shows an endoleak (pink arrows) around the chimney, leaking into the false lumen. The left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig9b.jpeg" height="1286" width="1392" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Chimney stent technique with parastent endoleak in a 64-year-old man. Catheter angiographic <b>(a)</b>, volume-rendered CT <b>(b)</b>, coronal CT <b>(c)</b>, and axial CT <b>(d)</b> images show deployment of a left common carotid artery stent (yellow arrow) parallel to the thoracic stent-graft. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. Axial CT image <b>(d)</b> shows an endoleak (pink arrows) around the chimney, leaking into the false lumen. The left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig9c.jpeg" height="1503" width="1516" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Chimney stent technique with parastent endoleak in a 64-year-old man. Catheter angiographic <b>(a)</b>, volume-rendered CT <b>(b)</b>, coronal CT <b>(c)</b>, and axial CT <b>(d)</b> images show deployment of a left common carotid artery stent (yellow arrow) parallel to the thoracic stent-graft. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. Axial CT image <b>(d)</b> shows an endoleak (pink arrows) around the chimney, leaking into the false lumen. The left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig9d.jpeg" height="1503" width="1420" aria-labelledby="fig9d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9d</span>. Chimney stent technique with parastent endoleak in a 64-year-old man. Catheter angiographic <b>(a)</b>, volume-rendered CT <b>(b)</b>, coronal CT <b>(c)</b>, and axial CT <b>(d)</b> images show deployment of a left common carotid artery stent (yellow arrow) parallel to the thoracic stent-graft. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. Axial CT image <b>(d)</b> shows an endoleak (pink arrows) around the chimney, leaking into the false lumen. The left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig9d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig10.jpeg" height="1359" width="3398" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span>. Anatomic drawings show TEVAR augmentation techniques in a zone 2 landing to deal with the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i>. Blue arrows = favorable flow. <i>1,</i> Anatomy before TEVAR, with a primary intimal tear <i>(PIT)</i>. Black arrows = favorable flow in the true lumen, white arrow = persistent flow into the false lumen. <i>2,</i> The left subclavian artery is covered with a stent without revascularization. <i>3,</i> Technique for fenestrated or branched left subclavian artery stent procedure. <i>4,</i> Carotid-subclavian artery transposition.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig11.jpeg" height="1461" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span>. Anatomic drawings show revascularization procedures in augmentation of a zone 1 landing. When TEVAR has to extend into zone 1, the left common carotid artery <i>(LCCA)</i> needs to undergo revascularization to prevent neurovascular compromise. This revascularization can be performed with a carotid-carotid crossover bypass with or without revascularization of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> at the same time. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, blue arrows = favorable flow. <i>1,</i> Bypass between the two carotid arteries is usually performed through a retropharyngeal tunnel, along with carotid-subclavian artery transposition. <i>2,</i> Subclavian-subclavian bypass with extrathoracic debranching technique for zone 0 sealing with TEVAR. This procedure and the axillary-axillary artery bypass with extrathoracic debranching technique for zone 0 sealing with TEVAR are rarely used. The double-chimney technique also is rarely used to rebuild both the left common carotid artery and the left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig12a.jpeg" height="1782" width="1126" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Augmentation of zone 1 landing in a 49-year-old man. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image was obtained after TEVAR was performed to repair a type B dissection with transposition (red arrow) of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> to the left common carotid artery. An endoleak into the false lumen persisted owing to retrograde filling of the left common carotid artery (arch vessel leak). The proximal landing zone is also covering part of the orifice of the left common carotid artery, which required revascularization of the left common carotid artery to prevent brain emboli. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained after carotid-carotid crossover bypass through a retropharyngeal tunnel (yellow arrows) shows that the endoleak has disappeared. Red arrow = transposition of the left subclavian artery to the left common carotid artery. Left inset on <b>b</b>: Sagittal CT image. Right inset on <b>b</b>: Axial CT image. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows thrombosis of the false lumen. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, <i>LSCA</i> = left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig12b.jpeg" height="1782" width="1312" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Augmentation of zone 1 landing in a 49-year-old man. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image was obtained after TEVAR was performed to repair a type B dissection with transposition (red arrow) of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> to the left common carotid artery. An endoleak into the false lumen persisted owing to retrograde filling of the left common carotid artery (arch vessel leak). The proximal landing zone is also covering part of the orifice of the left common carotid artery, which required revascularization of the left common carotid artery to prevent brain emboli. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained after carotid-carotid crossover bypass through a retropharyngeal tunnel (yellow arrows) shows that the endoleak has disappeared. Red arrow = transposition of the left subclavian artery to the left common carotid artery. Left inset on <b>b</b>: Sagittal CT image. Right inset on <b>b</b>: Axial CT image. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows thrombosis of the false lumen. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, <i>LSCA</i> = left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig12c.jpeg" height="1782" width="1270" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span>. Augmentation of zone 1 landing in a 49-year-old man. <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image was obtained after TEVAR was performed to repair a type B dissection with transposition (red arrow) of the left subclavian artery <i>(LSCA)</i> to the left common carotid artery. An endoleak into the false lumen persisted owing to retrograde filling of the left common carotid artery (arch vessel leak). The proximal landing zone is also covering part of the orifice of the left common carotid artery, which required revascularization of the left common carotid artery to prevent brain emboli. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery. <b>(b)</b> Coronal CT image obtained after carotid-carotid crossover bypass through a retropharyngeal tunnel (yellow arrows) shows that the endoleak has disappeared. Red arrow = transposition of the left subclavian artery to the left common carotid artery. Left inset on <b>b</b>: Sagittal CT image. Right inset on <b>b</b>: Axial CT image. <b>(c)</b> Coronal CT image shows thrombosis of the false lumen. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, <i>LSCA</i> = left subclavian artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig13a.jpeg" height="1273" width="1335" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Inadvertent partial coverage of the orifice (green arrow) of the left common carotid artery in an 81-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered CT image obtained after TEVAR shows that the left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery <i>(LCCA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images of the aortic arch before <b>(b)</b> and after <b>(c)</b> digital removal of the stent show a patent left common carotid artery. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig13b.jpeg" height="1299" width="1262" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Inadvertent partial coverage of the orifice (green arrow) of the left common carotid artery in an 81-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered CT image obtained after TEVAR shows that the left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery <i>(LCCA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images of the aortic arch before <b>(b)</b> and after <b>(c)</b> digital removal of the stent show a patent left common carotid artery. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig13c.jpeg" height="1309" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Inadvertent partial coverage of the orifice (green arrow) of the left common carotid artery in an 81-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Volume-rendered CT image obtained after TEVAR shows that the left subclavian artery was transposed to the left common carotid artery <i>(LCCA)</i>. <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images of the aortic arch before <b>(b)</b> and after <b>(c)</b> digital removal of the stent show a patent left common carotid artery. <i>InA</i> = innominate artery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig14.jpeg" height="4571" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Value of volumetric analysis, compared with planar measurements, in an 83-year-old woman with a chronic thoracoabdominal aortic aneurysm. Top row: Axial CT images obtained before TEVAR and later at follow-up after TEVAR. With these images alone, it would be difficult to define the behavior of the aortic dissection in the long run owing to the length of the aortic pathologic condition. Middle and bottom rows: Sagittal views show the results of volumetric measurements obtained from the left subclavian artery to the celiac trunk before TEVAR (middle row) and 4 months after TEVAR (bottom row); numbers in the yellow rectangles are volumes in milliliters. After stent placement, the patent lumen (images at left) decreased in volume, but the thrombosed part (images at right) increased. Insets (bottom row): Corresponding sagittal two-dimensional views can give the same impression, with the green area on the left inset showing the patent lumen and the green area on the right inset showing the thrombosed lumen. There was a 13% decrease in the total volume of the aorta (positive remodeling). At the 6-year follow-up, the thrombotic part became smaller.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig15.jpeg" height="4029" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span>. Concept of remodeling of the true and false lumina after TEVAR for type B aortic dissection in three different patients. Top row: Acute type B dissection in a 57-year-old man (case 1). Axial nonenhanced <i>(pre)</i> and contrast-enhanced <i>(post)</i> CT images obtained at arrival in the emergency department and at 1-month follow-up after TEVAR show rapid remodeling of both lumina in a short period after TEVAR. Middle row: Subacute type B dissection in a 42-year-old man (case 2). Axial CT images obtained before and after TEVAR show slower remodeling of both lumina during a 2-year period after TEVAR. Bottom row: TEVAR performed for a chronic type B dissection in a 43-year-old man (case 3). Axial CT images obtained after TEVAR show that because the false lumen is filled with organized thrombus and partially calcified, it did not remodel. As a result, the true lumen did not change either. In general, in acute and subacute type B dissection, most true lumen remodeling is complete within 6 months after TEVAR. Favorable remodeling of the false lumen in patients with subacute type B dissection is slower than that in patients with acute type B dissection; and in patients with chronic dissection, favorable remodeling is unpredictable and may never be achieved.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig16.jpeg" height="3275" width="3400" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span>. Fast post-TEVAR favorable remodeling of both the true and false lumina, and even of the aorta distal to the stent-graft and within the abdomen, in a 62-year-old woman with an acute type B dissection. Left to right: Axial CT images obtained at the level of the aortic arch (left), the diaphragm (middle), and the mid abdomen (right). Top row: Axial CT images obtained at the patient’s arrival in the emergency department show a marked expansion of the false lumen and the collapse of the true lumen that caused signs of hypoperfusion. TEVAR was performed immediately. Middle row: Axial CT images obtained immediately after TEVAR show that positive remodeling of the true lumen is seen instantly because of the closure of the primary tear and the lack of organized clot in the false lumen. Bottom row: Axial CT images obtained at 9-month follow-up show that although recovery from the abdominal dissection did not occur early, recovery was completed within 9 months.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig17.jpeg" height="2085" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span>. Remodeling at the level of the stent compared with remodeling in the area distal to the stent in a 49-year-old man with a type B dissection. TEVAR was performed because of interval enlargement of the descending aorta, including the false lumen <i>(FL)</i>. Top row: Axial CT images obtained at the level of the chest show that at the stent level, the remodeling of both the false lumen and the true lumen <i>(TL)</i> was completed favorably. Bottom row: Axial CT images obtained at the level of the abdomen show that the opposite occurred in the segment distal to the stent, including in the abdomen. Negative remodeling (enlargement) of the abdominal aortic false lumen is depicted at late follow-up (4 years after TEVAR) (bottom row, far right).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig18.jpeg" height="2072" width="2300" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. Anatomic drawing shows the causes of pressurization owing to persistent false lumen refilling and/or endoleak after primary surgical repair of type A aortic dissection or after TEVAR for type B aortic dissection. The underlying causes are grouped into proximal refill and distal refill in the boxes at right. Black arrow within the vessel lumen = favorable flow in the true lumen, blue arrows = favorable flow, white arrows = persistent flow into the false lumen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig19.jpeg" height="1706" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig19" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen. Diastolic pressure in the false lumen is highest in the setting of a large proximal tear and small or absent distal reentries. Anatomic drawings show two postsurgical models (<i>1</i> and <i>2</i>). <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, black arrows within the lumen = favorable flow in the true lumen, blue arrows = favorable flow, white arrows = persistent flow into and within the false lumen. Left: Model 1 is after primary replacement of the ascending aorta, with persistent retrograde filling of the false lumen from the innominate artery <i>(InA)</i> and with antegrade filling from a proximal tear. A laminar thrombus (distal clot) occludes the distal tear, aggravating expansion of the false lumen. Right: Model 2 shows that despite aortic arch replacement and revascularization of the arch vessels, the problem with filling of the false lumen has not resolved. The false lumen is now filling through a leaking distal anastomosis, as well as through small-scale antegrade filling from a proximal tear. Both of these two scenarios require TEVAR. If the visceral vessels arise off both the true and false lumina or predominantly off the false lumen, fenestration of the intimal septum is also required.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig19">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig20.jpeg" height="2476" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen in a 53-year-old man after repair of a type A aortic dissection. Axial early phase (top left), axial late phase (top right), coronal late phase (bottom left), and 7-month follow-up (bottom right) CT angiographic images show that this case is similar to model 1 (<a href="#fig19">Fig 19</a>), in which repair of the ascending aorta was performed for type A dissection, but there was persistent filling of the false lumen <i>(FL)</i> from retrograde flow (yellow arrow) in an innominate artery <i>(InA)</i> dissection. In addition to retrograde flow in the innominate artery, delayed emptying of the false lumen is depicted on the axial late phase image (top right). This sign is an important radiologic finding that indicates a lack of sufficient distal drainage of the false lumen and the potential for growth of the false lumen. The 7-month follow-up image (bottom right) shows the increasing size of the false lumen. The patient underwent surgery, and the surgery extended to the arch (see <a href="#fig21a">Fig 21</a> for the outcome).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig21a.jpeg" height="1427" width="1295" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Inadvertent stent-graft implantation in the false lumen in a 53-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig20">Fig 20</a>) with a repaired type A aortic dissection. The patient underwent arch repair and graft reimplantation of the carotid arteries to treat retrograde refilling of the false lumen from the innominate artery. TEVAR was then performed. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show inadvertent placement of the stent in the false lumen, as well as persistent collapse of the true lumen and an enlarged false lumen. Red arrows within the lumina = flow in the true and false lumina. Because of these findings, CT angiography was performed 2 months later. Intravascular Doppler color US (not shown) demonstrated antegrade flow in the false lumen and retrograde flow in the true lumen. Because the distal fenestrae depicted at CT and intravascular US were small, a distal fenestration procedure was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT angiographic images obtained before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> the fenestration procedure show that a new large fenestra (orange arrow on <b>d</b>) was created by balloon expansion at the level of the L1 vertebra (<i>L1</i> on <b>c</b>). Inset on <b>d</b>: Frontal radiograph shows the waist of the distended balloon at the level of the fenestration. In this case, only a distal fenestration procedure was performed, and follow-up imaging at 2 years after the procedure showed no substantial change except thrombosis of the true lumen at the level of the stent. That is why some surgeons suggest endovascular revision including distal extension of the stent-graft into the true lumen in addition to septal fenestration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig21b.jpeg" height="1427" width="1358" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Inadvertent stent-graft implantation in the false lumen in a 53-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig20">Fig 20</a>) with a repaired type A aortic dissection. The patient underwent arch repair and graft reimplantation of the carotid arteries to treat retrograde refilling of the false lumen from the innominate artery. TEVAR was then performed. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show inadvertent placement of the stent in the false lumen, as well as persistent collapse of the true lumen and an enlarged false lumen. Red arrows within the lumina = flow in the true and false lumina. Because of these findings, CT angiography was performed 2 months later. Intravascular Doppler color US (not shown) demonstrated antegrade flow in the false lumen and retrograde flow in the true lumen. Because the distal fenestrae depicted at CT and intravascular US were small, a distal fenestration procedure was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT angiographic images obtained before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> the fenestration procedure show that a new large fenestra (orange arrow on <b>d</b>) was created by balloon expansion at the level of the L1 vertebra (<i>L1</i> on <b>c</b>). Inset on <b>d</b>: Frontal radiograph shows the waist of the distended balloon at the level of the fenestration. In this case, only a distal fenestration procedure was performed, and follow-up imaging at 2 years after the procedure showed no substantial change except thrombosis of the true lumen at the level of the stent. That is why some surgeons suggest endovascular revision including distal extension of the stent-graft into the true lumen in addition to septal fenestration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig21c.jpeg" height="1252" width="1271" aria-labelledby="fig21c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21c</span>. Inadvertent stent-graft implantation in the false lumen in a 53-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig20">Fig 20</a>) with a repaired type A aortic dissection. The patient underwent arch repair and graft reimplantation of the carotid arteries to treat retrograde refilling of the false lumen from the innominate artery. TEVAR was then performed. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show inadvertent placement of the stent in the false lumen, as well as persistent collapse of the true lumen and an enlarged false lumen. Red arrows within the lumina = flow in the true and false lumina. Because of these findings, CT angiography was performed 2 months later. Intravascular Doppler color US (not shown) demonstrated antegrade flow in the false lumen and retrograde flow in the true lumen. Because the distal fenestrae depicted at CT and intravascular US were small, a distal fenestration procedure was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT angiographic images obtained before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> the fenestration procedure show that a new large fenestra (orange arrow on <b>d</b>) was created by balloon expansion at the level of the L1 vertebra (<i>L1</i> on <b>c</b>). Inset on <b>d</b>: Frontal radiograph shows the waist of the distended balloon at the level of the fenestration. In this case, only a distal fenestration procedure was performed, and follow-up imaging at 2 years after the procedure showed no substantial change except thrombosis of the true lumen at the level of the stent. That is why some surgeons suggest endovascular revision including distal extension of the stent-graft into the true lumen in addition to septal fenestration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig21c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig21d.jpeg" height="1256" width="1376" aria-labelledby="fig21d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21d</span>. Inadvertent stent-graft implantation in the false lumen in a 53-year-old man (same patient as in <a href="#fig20">Fig 20</a>) with a repaired type A aortic dissection. The patient underwent arch repair and graft reimplantation of the carotid arteries to treat retrograde refilling of the false lumen from the innominate artery. TEVAR was then performed. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show inadvertent placement of the stent in the false lumen, as well as persistent collapse of the true lumen and an enlarged false lumen. Red arrows within the lumina = flow in the true and false lumina. Because of these findings, CT angiography was performed 2 months later. Intravascular Doppler color US (not shown) demonstrated antegrade flow in the false lumen and retrograde flow in the true lumen. Because the distal fenestrae depicted at CT and intravascular US were small, a distal fenestration procedure was performed. <b>(c, d)</b> Axial CT angiographic images obtained before <b>(c)</b> and after <b>(d)</b> the fenestration procedure show that a new large fenestra (orange arrow on <b>d</b>) was created by balloon expansion at the level of the L1 vertebra (<i>L1</i> on <b>c</b>). Inset on <b>d</b>: Frontal radiograph shows the waist of the distended balloon at the level of the fenestration. In this case, only a distal fenestration procedure was performed, and follow-up imaging at 2 years after the procedure showed no substantial change except thrombosis of the true lumen at the level of the stent. That is why some surgeons suggest endovascular revision including distal extension of the stent-graft into the true lumen in addition to septal fenestration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig21d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig22.jpeg" height="2630" width="2700" aria-labelledby="fig22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 22</span>. Early and late remodeling in the descending thoracic aortic false lumen after primary surgery for type A dissection followed by TEVAR in a 62-year-old man. Top row: Volume-rendered CT images. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta, <i>InA</i> = innominate artery, <i>LCCA</i> = left common carotid artery, <i>LSCA</i> = left subclavian artery. Top left: Volume-rendered CT image of the results of the elephant trunk technique shows persistent filling (yellow arrow) of the false lumen through a proximal intimal tear (dashed white oval). Top right: Volume-rendered CT image shows the findings after secondary TEVAR was performed because of the negative remodeling of the false lumen. TEVAR was performed after transposition of the left subclavian artery to the left common carotid artery. Bottom row: Follow-up serial axial CT images obtained in various years (2011–2014) show fast positive remodeling of the true lumen, but the remodeling of the false lumen takes time. <i>AA</i> = ascending aorta.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig23a.jpeg" height="1170" width="894" aria-labelledby="fig23a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23a</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to distal stent collapse in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at arrival in the emergency department shows a type B aortic dissection. <i>LCSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images obtained at 10 days after TEVAR show the collapse of the distal stent (yellow arrow on <b>c</b>). The stent covers the left subclavian artery partially. Also depicted is a relatively large endoleak (red arrow) superior to the proximal landing zone; the endoleak was arising from the left subclavian artery and was attributed to changes in the hemodynamics after the severe collapse of the distal stent, shifting flow toward the false lumen. <b>(d)</b> Axial follow-up CT images obtained at 4 months after correction of the collapse (yellow arrow) show resolution of the proximal endoleak (blue arrow). Excessive oversizing has been reported as the primary cause of endograft collapse.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig23a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig23b.jpeg" height="1170" width="854" aria-labelledby="fig23b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23b</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to distal stent collapse in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at arrival in the emergency department shows a type B aortic dissection. <i>LCSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images obtained at 10 days after TEVAR show the collapse of the distal stent (yellow arrow on <b>c</b>). The stent covers the left subclavian artery partially. Also depicted is a relatively large endoleak (red arrow) superior to the proximal landing zone; the endoleak was arising from the left subclavian artery and was attributed to changes in the hemodynamics after the severe collapse of the distal stent, shifting flow toward the false lumen. <b>(d)</b> Axial follow-up CT images obtained at 4 months after correction of the collapse (yellow arrow) show resolution of the proximal endoleak (blue arrow). Excessive oversizing has been reported as the primary cause of endograft collapse.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig23b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig23c.jpeg" height="961" width="1900" aria-labelledby="fig23c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23c</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to distal stent collapse in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at arrival in the emergency department shows a type B aortic dissection. <i>LCSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images obtained at 10 days after TEVAR show the collapse of the distal stent (yellow arrow on <b>c</b>). The stent covers the left subclavian artery partially. Also depicted is a relatively large endoleak (red arrow) superior to the proximal landing zone; the endoleak was arising from the left subclavian artery and was attributed to changes in the hemodynamics after the severe collapse of the distal stent, shifting flow toward the false lumen. <b>(d)</b> Axial follow-up CT images obtained at 4 months after correction of the collapse (yellow arrow) show resolution of the proximal endoleak (blue arrow). Excessive oversizing has been reported as the primary cause of endograft collapse.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig23c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig23d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig23d.jpeg" height="961" width="1839" aria-labelledby="fig23d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 23d</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to distal stent collapse in a 62-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal CT image obtained at arrival in the emergency department shows a type B aortic dissection. <i>LCSA</i> = left subclavian artery. <b>(b, c)</b> Sagittal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> CT images obtained at 10 days after TEVAR show the collapse of the distal stent (yellow arrow on <b>c</b>). The stent covers the left subclavian artery partially. Also depicted is a relatively large endoleak (red arrow) superior to the proximal landing zone; the endoleak was arising from the left subclavian artery and was attributed to changes in the hemodynamics after the severe collapse of the distal stent, shifting flow toward the false lumen. <b>(d)</b> Axial follow-up CT images obtained at 4 months after correction of the collapse (yellow arrow) show resolution of the proximal endoleak (blue arrow). Excessive oversizing has been reported as the primary cause of endograft collapse.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig23d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig24a.jpeg" height="1404" width="1213" aria-labelledby="fig24a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24a</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to stent-induced intimal blowout in a 41-year-old man with type B aortic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images obtained at initial imaging after TEVAR show rupture of the detached intima by the inferior edge of the stent (red arrow on <b>a</b>), the so-called intimal blowout, which causes entrance of blood into the distal part of the false lumen and pressurization of the false lumen. The false lumen remained enlarged (yellow double-headed arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal <b>(c)</b> and axial <b>(d)</b> CT images obtained 1 month after the addition of a distal stent extending to the diaphragm show rapid favorable remodeling of the true lumen and of the false lumen (double-headed pink arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig24a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig24b.jpeg" height="1404" width="1436" aria-labelledby="fig24b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24b</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to stent-induced intimal blowout in a 41-year-old man with type B aortic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images obtained at initial imaging after TEVAR show rupture of the detached intima by the inferior edge of the stent (red arrow on <b>a</b>), the so-called intimal blowout, which causes entrance of blood into the distal part of the false lumen and pressurization of the false lumen. The false lumen remained enlarged (yellow double-headed arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal <b>(c)</b> and axial <b>(d)</b> CT images obtained 1 month after the addition of a distal stent extending to the diaphragm show rapid favorable remodeling of the true lumen and of the false lumen (double-headed pink arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig24b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig24c.jpeg" height="1331" width="1213" aria-labelledby="fig24c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24c</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to stent-induced intimal blowout in a 41-year-old man with type B aortic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images obtained at initial imaging after TEVAR show rupture of the detached intima by the inferior edge of the stent (red arrow on <b>a</b>), the so-called intimal blowout, which causes entrance of blood into the distal part of the false lumen and pressurization of the false lumen. The false lumen remained enlarged (yellow double-headed arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal <b>(c)</b> and axial <b>(d)</b> CT images obtained 1 month after the addition of a distal stent extending to the diaphragm show rapid favorable remodeling of the true lumen and of the false lumen (double-headed pink arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig24c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig24d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018180025/asset/images/large/rg.2018180025.fig24d.jpeg" height="1331" width="1442" aria-labelledby="fig24d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 24d</span>. Failing remodeling of the false lumen owing to stent-induced intimal blowout in a 41-year-old man with type B aortic dissection. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT angiographic images obtained at initial imaging after TEVAR show rupture of the detached intima by the inferior edge of the stent (red arrow on <b>a</b>), the so-called intimal blowout, which causes entrance of blood into the distal part of the false lumen and pressurization of the false lumen. The false lumen remained enlarged (yellow double-headed arrow). <b>(c, d)</b> Sagittal <b>(c)</b> and axial <b>(d)</b> CT images obtained 1 month after the addition of a distal stent extending to the diaphragm show rapid favorable remodeling of the true lumen and of the false lumen (double-headed pink arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018180025&amp;id=fig24d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Pape LA, Awais M, Woznicki EM, et al. Presentation, diagnosis, and outcomes of acute aortic dissection: 17- year trends from the Internationa